The difference is that r/k selection theory involves the quality of upbringing just as much as the number of offspring.
There's also the matter that in every known sentient species (just us lol lmao) you have the phenomenon you mentioned not always being the case.
In ye olden times, serfs and commoners would have large families because it meant more helping hands, and when you grew old more people to take care of you.
In the same period, nobles also had lots of children, and for the same reason.
Today, there is no incentive for large families unless you're poor, because middle to upper class families only lose wealth from children while poor families (I know what sort of people you're thinking of. So while r vs k is an interesting concepts, I don't think it is relevant to social status in humans.
